"It is still time, Mr. Godall, to make good your escape into thraldom. And
                       for you too, Major Hammersmith. Reflect well before you take another step;
                       and if your hearts say no--here are the crossroads."

"But I perceive I am still in the dark. You speak of shuffling and dealing;
                       pray, for what end? And since you seem rather unwilling to die than
                       otherwise, I must own that I cannot conceive what brings you here at all."

The General once more raised his cane, and made a cut for Charlie's head;
                       but the latter, lame foot and all, evaded the blow with his umbrella, ran
                       in, and immediately closed with his formidable adversary.

"Who are you?" he demanded at last. "Who are you to come flying over my wall
                       and break my Gloire de Dijons? What is your name?" he added, shaking him;
                       "and what may be your business here?"

"They are not yours, are they not?" returned Raeburn. "And you could not
                       share them with anybody, couldn't you? Well now, that is what I call a pity;
                       for here am I obliged to take you to the station. The police--think of
                       that," he continued; "think of the disgrace for your respectable parents;
                       think," he went on, taking Harry by the wrist; "think of the Colonies and
                       the Day of Judgment."

"Be it so," said she. "You do not know what you ask, but be it so. Whatever
                       you hear," she continued, "whatever happens, do not return to this house;
                       hurry fast until you reach the lighted and populous quarters of the city;
                       even there be upon your guard. You are in a greater danger than you fancy.
                       Promise me you will not so much as look at my keepsake until you are in a
                       place of safety."
